// Fires when the D1 index database approaches its 10 GB hard cap (threshold at
// 7 GiB — the plan's warning level, where the escape hatches kick in: tighten
// truncation caps -> drop tool_use input from FTS -> shard blocks+FTS by year)
// OR when the size probe itself is broken.
//
// Source: the hub watchdog cron (*/15) emits, once per run, a structured log
//   { event: "hub.d1.db_size_bytes", bytes: <n> }
// (hub/src/cron/watchdog.ts). On a healthy probe `bytes` is the real size; if
// the PRAGMA probe fails or returns nothing the watchdog emits `bytes: -1` as
// an explicit failing signal (rather than dropping the metric, which would make
// this alert blind exactly when the probe breaks while heartbeat_age keeps
// missed-heartbeat.kql "healthy"). So this fires on `bytes < 0` (probe broken)
// as well as `bytes > 7 GiB` (cap approaching); the email's bytes value
// distinguishes the two. Workers observability ships it to Log Analytics
// OTelLogs (Body = that JSON) — same path/column as missed-heartbeat.kql
// (verified live 2026-07-17).
//
// A 1h window comfortably contains a watchdog emission (it runs every 15 min);
// we take the most recent reported size. `bytes` is pulled out with `extend`
// before the `arg_max` (rather than aliased inside it) for clarity — both forms
// execute (verified live against a synthetic 8 GB row), this one is unambiguous.
// No pipeline-silent sentinel is needed here: total telemetry silence is already
// covered by missed-heartbeat.kql's __pipeline_silent__ row.

OTelLogs
| where TimeGenerated > ago(1h)
| extend body = todynamic(Body)
| where body.event == "hub.d1.db_size_bytes"
| extend bytes = tolong(body.bytes)
| summarize arg_max(TimeGenerated, bytes)
| where bytes < 0 or bytes > 7 * 1024 * 1024 * 1024
| project TimeGenerated, bytes
